Alamin is phenomenal. He will go down as one of the best CEOs of our genera=
tion, for a couple of reasons. First, he genuinely thinks on a multi-decade=
 time horizon. Second, he has a Stripe-like bar for talent. Even the qualit=
y of candidates he turns down is incredibly high. He=E2=80=99s building a t=
alent powerhouse.
As evidence of that, over the past twelve months, NexHealth has built a lea=
dership team from Netflix, Upwork, Redfin, Marketo, Optimizely, Amplitude, =
SAP, and more. The leaders they hired from those companies were early -- al=
l except for the SAP and Redfin hires started when the companies were under=
 30 employees -- and scaled the companies through IPO. Hiring people who=E2=
=80=99ve scaled from zero to public is a good way to reduce execution risk.=
 Overall, the team grew 6x over the past year, from under 20 to 120 employe=
es. Meanwhile, it grew customers by over 300%.
NexHealth is growing fast. Customers love its SaaS product (it has a perfec=
t 5 stars on Capterra [https://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxFkEtuxCAMQE8zLCP=
-IQsW3VRd9QoRHydBk0AEpGluX2ayqATYwrKe_ZypMKd86T2Vil7PWK8ddISzrFArZHQUyGPwmk=
iqmOAD8pp7ooRCoYxTBthMWHXNB6D9sGtwpoYU3x0YU4EWbY2nXnDKMfaMyclR2w-DhAl7wrDsb=
645fIDoQMMP5CtFQKteat3Lg3086Gc753l2zuxtqGw6l7b2tbdLFKU9ack3_H6BWevSchQ0xZRg=
STmhjS070klHqBPe-V6ANdBGGoj11g3eMCfU9OB4m2lXDluqcc8XAmUdU7Uphzi38nMxG6zvQtt=
1bHE7YqjXCNHYFfytod4232LGGSLkZtmPpr4ccsEG2ivB1b1288T6QShBJGpkn1pX_If-ASuPio=
8]). It=E2=80=99s already built out a public-facing API used by small busin=
esses, independent developers, and public companies alike. Month-over-month=
 gross churn is below 0.5% and MoM net retention is over 100%. It has the r=
ight team in place.=C2=A0=C2=A0
NexHealth exceeds expectations for a startup at its stage. On its current t=
rajectory, the company could well be worth a few billion dollars in the com=
ing years. But that=E2=80=99s not the goal; $100 billion is. To build a $10=
0 billion company that accelerates innovation in healthcare, its team needs=
 to execute on building clean infrastructure for healthcare.=C2=A0
Easier and Harder Than Ever=C2=A0
There=E2=80=99s an interesting bifurcation happening in software startups.
For most startups, it=E2=80=99s never been faster or easier to build a prod=
uct. That=E2=80=99s largely because of how much good infrastructure has bee=
n built over the past decade. In Ramp=E2=80=99s Double-Unicorn Rounds [http=
s://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxFkEuKwzAMQE9T7xr8TZ2FF7OZawR_1MQ0sYPtTMjtR2=
1gBiwLJMSTnrcNplxOs-XayPsb27mBSXDUBVqDQvYKZYzBsJ5roeRAgpGBaaVJrOOzAKw2LqaVH=
ci2uyV622JOnwlKuSKzeQorwAOXXEjrlAdGnQ6UMh8enHJxce0eIiQPBn6gnDkBWczc2lZv4uvG=
v_Edx9Gl3FwuMU2dz1jaMIpdt3oPGeFw31P0uaR7yXsK9e5gjimQaJDDaM8l40ryvmNd7xn3KuA=
KCpyFgJcxF5wfghVe6edN0nXiXd1dbda_ELeSYv7w2H7NdoXl08DDR8wr0ts5QrK4SrictEvtx9=
I4QYKCysNo21uoVGLgD62kvhygNPEYlFasJ0gOGafSP_QXaf6STQ], I wrote:=C2=A0
Today, a top engineering team can take so much good software off the shelf =
that development timelines have been dramatically compressed. Logan Bartlet=
t [https://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxFkEuOxCAMRE_TLKPwy2fBYjZzjQiwO42GQAT=
OtHL7IZ3FSMjIsuyqet4SrrmcZs-V2FUWOnc0Cd81IhEWdlQsSwDDBzFJrWYGRgGf9MRCXZ4Fcb=
MhGioHsv1wMXhLIafPRt8LzV5GyxG8ld4-neNuBGdhVlwrr4cZeyluXXtAwOTR4C-WMydk0byI9=
vqQXw_x3R69w-Wo83lrXcyrTc4WunyyYEQveD8IxYVWYuh4N3guvAYPo0ZnEZp37sD5GZoXPT0f=
qt9W0dXDVbL-5zrLikmZXC4hrW3887Ibxs-gRVvavx0p0Llgsi4i3KnphvfhsKyYsDSosFi6kCk=
tZzFOWk13yoZFjrOeNB9YU4bcttK_6B_H0Yfw], a VC at Redpoint, guessed that just=
 a decade ago, it would have taken seven or eight years for even a great co=
mpany to build what Ramp did in two.
But for the startups building the software that those other startups get to=
 take off the shelf, it=E2=80=99s never been harder.=C2=A0
Infrastructure-via-API has become such an obviously strong position in the =
value chain that any of the remotely easy spots have been grabbed, leaving =
only the hardest of the hard. Healthcare infrastructure, which requires int=
egrating with Electronic Health Records (EHRs) and Electronic Medical Recor=
ds (EMRs) in the thousand places they live today, fits the bill.=C2=A0
For the most part, the consumer experience in healthcare sucks. There are p=
lenty of good excuses -- regulation is overly complex, incentives are misal=
igned, insurance is a racket -- and no one technology company can solve tho=
se directly. But technology companies can build infrastructure to unleash t=
he collective energy of thousands of entrepreneurs on the problem.
In spaces in which good infrastructure exists, hungry entrepreneurs can sna=
p together different building blocks in the backend, and spend most of thei=
r time focusing on a good and differentiated experience on the front-end. I=
n APIs All the Way Down [https://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxFkE2OhCAQRk_T7=
NpICYgLFrOZaxh-SiWtYADHePuh22QmKaoSKpWX71ldcI7pUnvMhbzbWK4dVcAzr1gKJnJkTKN3=
igqQHWcDcYo5KrkkPo9TQty0X1VJB5L9MKu3uvgYPhdtC5wsikM3aQsdsEkjg95Q5oR0A7QTnag=
QN1cfzmOwqPAH0xUDklUtpez50X094LvWeZ5NiMXE5MPc2Fi_9vr07vNTr-uzLPg89fV08QzEK2=
iBtgIYBc5ANLQRloLlzrqeo9HoahhqnLGD053lcnqwdpuhyYfJRdtXJWwkqT9iXb8WveH6WdSsY=
53bEXy5RgzarOhuDeW2-REzzhgwVctu1OXtkPFugF5yJu_Y1VPXD1xyKkglu1ivwj_0F952jJg]=
, I described the impact that has:=C2=A0
This is the beauty of API-first companies. They allow customers to focus on=
 the one or two things that differentiate their businesses, while plugging =
in best-in-class solutions everywhere else.=C2=A0
Without that infrastructure, though, teams waste time and resources reinven=
ting the wheel. Many, daunted or overwhelmed by everything it would take to=
 build even a good enough product skip the space entirely and opt for somet=
hing smoother. You don=E2=80=99t see a lot of 17-year-olds hacking on healt=
htech in their bedroom.=C2=A0
Specifically, in healthtech, the challenge is that there are thousands of E=
HRs that are tiny, fragmented, and antiquated, many of which don=E2=80=99t =
have APIs at all. That means there=E2=80=99s no one System of Record, or so=
urce of truth, that anyone building products can tap into to understand eve=
rything about a patient. Your dental records may be hidden in one system, p=
rimary care records in another, hospital records in another, insurance info=
rmation elsewhere, and so on.=20
NexHealth exists to fix that. If NexHealth is successful, in a decade or ev=
en longer, a new generation of entrepreneurs will be able to build healthte=
ch products as easily as they=E2=80=99re able to build fintech products tod=
ay.=C2=A0
It will do for healthtech what Plaid did for fintech.=C2=A0
How Plaid Started
To understand NexHealth=E2=80=99s strategy, you first need to understand Pl=
aid [https://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxFUMtuxCAM_JrlGAXC88Chl_4G4uFk0RKIg=
LTK35fdHCpZtqXReDzjbYet1EsfpXX0bqZfB-gMvy1B71DR2aCaGDTmRC6MKhQ0DVgyiWIzawXY=
bUy61xPQcboUve2x5A9jnglDT22pUI5TtlollFd2pVxwC4GSRTAv3K1rzxAhe9DwA_UqGVDSz96=
P9li-HuR71JFsDJMv-9hR1GQmeOaEYsIo4ROeuMfEs-CDYODG_fEsdsF5FezimVwfdN43MrXTtW=
79630JVZ1Ld6XGvA349bQ7pA8wvJgx9zPHfhnI1iUIt81-p_UxbjbIUEeKwdj-zoiyRREhGZW3r=
ZHDIhSTDHM0lEMZrPwv-gdUEYEK].=C2=A0
Plaid is an API-first company that lets developers connect their apps to pe=
oples=E2=80=99 bank accounts. If you=E2=80=99ve tried to fund an account, l=
ike Robinhood or Coinbase, using your bank account, you=E2=80=99ve likely c=
onnected via Plaid. If you use an app that pulls all of your financial data=
 into one place, you=E2=80=99ve likely added all of your accounts by loggin=
g in via Plaid. Developers love Plaid because instead of having to integrat=
e with thousands of different banks, all with different requirements, and t=
hen maintain all of those integrations, they just integrate with Plaid. Pla=
id does the rest.=C2=A0
Source: Justin Gage, Technically [https://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxVkMGO=
hCAMhp9muI0RFNQDh73saxigHSWDYKDuxLdfZjxsNqG0yZ_2z_85Q7ikfOo9FWLvb6ZzRx3xVQI=
SYWZHwTx70FyJsZP9xED3wEc5Ml_mR0bcjA-a8oFsP2zwzpBP8bPRtkKyVbfArVQ4IAgxtIpziY=
ZPZpJGOQXOXr7mAI_RocYfzGeKyIJeifZy675u4rs-QrfGej-EsymHLWTcs3Fpq9Je67UaukPCc=
t-D8VBH5rVoBW-V6LmQvVANb5TjwklwMEi0BqEm4hasm8B0To6PW99ui_h3n2UdE9mUfVyq_FzN=
huEj1MBz7dsRPZ0zRmMDwsWCLqQfOvOCEXNFDbOhN8hedpMYRtmPV_YKqxsmOUquWHWGVLfin-k=
vYLiO-g]
Today, Plaid partners with nearly every major bank, and many smaller ones, =
but back in 2013 when Plaid launched, it didn=E2=80=99t. What bank would tr=
ust a young startup with its customers=E2=80=99 credentials? So Plaid got c=
reative.=C2=A0
Venmo was Plaid=E2=80=99s first big customer, accounting for roughly 40% of=
 its revenue in the first few years. Instead of Venmo integrating with all =
of the banks itself, it plugged in Plaid via API. When a Venmo user set up =
an account, they chose their bank and entered their credentials via Plaid, =
and Plaid logged in on their behalf. Plaid manually scraped, pulling inform=
ation from the bank account and making transfers to Venmo on users=E2=80=99=
 behalf. Like the Wizard of Oz, Plaid looked like a fancy, integrated tech =
product on the front-end, but was really just a screen-scraping man behind =
the curtain.=C2=A0
Some banks tried to stop Plaid, but eventually, Plaid got big enough that b=
anks had no choice but to play ball. If their customers couldn=E2=80=99t us=
e Venmo=C2=A0 or any other number of fintech apps because their bank blocke=
d Plaid, that might be a good enough reason to switch to a new bank.=C2=A0
Today, Plaid is massive. It partners directly with banks. Visa tried to buy=
 Plaid for $5.3 billion in 2020. The Department of Justice blocked it on an=
titrust grounds. In seven years, Plaid had become so enmeshed in the financ=
ial plumbing that the government thought that Visa owning Plaid would creat=
e a monopoly. It worked out well for Plaid, though. In April, Altimeter led=
 a $425 million Series D [https://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxFUcGO6yAM_Jpy=
owICSXrgsJf3G5EBp0GbQARmn_r3S9rDSmiMsOwZZjwQPnN52TNXYhcs9DrRJvxfdyTCwlrFssR=
g5ajmwegHC1YHOZuZxbqsBfGAuFsqDdnZ3B49UMzpPSGEMmyzXuCsVuXMiKuToFZYJyXcNE5hlp=
MRH15oIWLyaPEHyysnZLvdiM56G75u6l8_hH7zpSW_3X0--oMSSvYi9AVTh3OHGHiBWLFyrczBu=
_jY74GvJR8cdooH9l9xqDwS9xsUqhz4pYD_xAp8bdQK9l0s2mu_GJWWymg13uV99FJ5E3yYDDrA=
